│ **Understanding the Issue**\nThe issue lies in the           │
│ `loop-peel` transformation when applied to a loop where the  │
│ exit condition is computed in one basic block                │
│ (`loop.header`) and used in another (`loop.latch`). The      │
│ transformation incorrectly remaps the uses of the exit       │
│ condition in the peeled iteration.\n\nIn the original loop,  │
│ the exit condition `%ec` is calculated in `loop.header`. The │
│ peeled iteration should use a new exit condition,            │
│ `%ec.peel`, calculated within the peeled blocks. However,    │
│ during the peeling process, when `loop.latch` is cloned to   │
│ create `loop.latch.peel`, the terminator `br i1 %ec, label   │
│ %exit, label %loop.header` is not correctly updated.         │
│ Specifically, the use of `%ec` is not remapped to            │
│ `%ec.peel`. Instead, it is incorrectly remapped to a         │
│ constant `true` because the original edge from `loop.latch`  │
│ to `loop.header` is considered part of the backedge, and its │
│ condition is evaluated as if the loop is always taken. This  │
│ leads to the branch in `loop.latch.peel` becoming `br i1     │
│ true, label %exit.peel.next, label %exit.peel.next`, which   │
│ is effectively an unconditional branch.\n\nThe Alive2        │
│ verifier detects a discrepancy because the original loop has │
│ a defined exit, while the transformed loop (due to the       │
│ incorrect branch condition) might behave differently,        │
│ leading to the \"failed-to-prove\" error. The verifier's     │
│ message \"The source program doesn't reach a return          │
│ instruction\" is a bit misleading; it's a symptom of the     │
│ verifier being unable to prove equivalence, not necessarily  │
│ an infinite loop in the transformed code itself.\n\n2.       │
│ **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**\nThe `opt` log shows that the      │
│ `loop-unroll` pass decides to peel the loop: `PEELING loop   │
│ %loop.header with iteration count 1!`. The backtrace         │
│ confirms that the transformation happens within              │
│ `llvm::peelLoop`, which calls `SplitEdge` and subsequently   │
│ `BasicBlock::splitBasicBlockBefore`. The issue arises during │
│ the remapping of values within the peeled blocks, which is a │
│ core part of the `peelLoop` logic.\n\n3. **Root Cause        │
│ Analysis**\nThe root cause is a flaw in `LoopPeel.cpp`. When │
│ `peelLoop` clones the basic blocks of the original loop to   │
│ create the peeled iteration, it uses                         │
│ `CloneAndRemapBasicBlock` to duplicate the blocks and remap  │
│ instruction operands.\n\nThe problem occurs when remapping   │
│ the terminator of `loop.latch`. The original terminator is   │
│ `br i1 %ec, label %exit, label %loop.header`. In the peeled  │
│ version, `loop.latch.peel`, this should become `br i1        │
│ %ec.peel, label %exit.peel.next, label                       │
│ %loop.header.peel.next`.\n\nHowever, the remapping logic for │
│ the branch condition `%ec` is faulty. The `ValueMap` used    │
│ for remapping is populated with an entry for the edge from   │
│ `loop.latch` to `loop.header` (the backedge). The condition  │
│ for this backedge is incorrectly determined to be `true`     │
│ because the peeling logic assumes that for the backedge, the │
│ loop continues. When `CloneAndRemapBasicBlock` encounters    │
│ the use of `%ec` in the terminator, it finds this mapping    │
│ and replaces `%ec` with                                      │
│ `ConstantInt::get(Type::getInt1Ty(C), 1)`, i.e.,             │
│ `true`.\n\nThis results in the terminator of                 │
│ `loop.latch.peel` becoming `br i1 true, label                │
│ %exit.peel.next, label %exit.peel.next`, which is not        │
│ semantically equivalent to the original loop's behavior. The │
│ condition should have been the peeled exit condition,        │
│ `%ec.peel`.\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when remapping the  │
│ terminator of the latch block, we explicitly use the peeled  │
│ exit condition (`PeeledCond`) instead of relying on the      │
│ potentially incorrect mapping in the `ValueMap`.\n\n4.       │
│ **Proposed Edit Point(s)**\nThe fix involves modifying       │
│ `llvm::peelLoop` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp` │
│ to correctly handle the terminator of the latch block in the │
│ peeled iteration.\n\n```cpp\nFile:                           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp\nLines:               │
│ 1139-1141\n---\n  // The new latch needs to jump to the old  │
│ header.\n  RemapInstruction(NewLatch->getTerminator(),       │
│ VMap,\n                   RF_NoModuleLevelChanges |          │
│ RF_IgnoreMissingLocals);\n---\nbecomes\n---\n  // The new    │
│ latch needs to jump to the old header.\n  Instruction        │
│ *NewTerm = NewLatch->getTerminator();\n  if (PeeledCond)\n   │
│ NewTerm->setOperand(0, PeeledCond);\n                        │
│ RemapInstruction(NewTerm, VMap,\n                            │
│ RF_NoModuleLevelChanges |                                    │
│ RF_IgnoreMissingLocals);\n---\n```\n\nThis change explicitly │
│ sets the condition of the new latch's terminator to          │
│ `PeeledCond` (the exit condition for the peeled iteration)   │
│ if it exists. This overrides the incorrect mapping that      │
│ `RemapInstruction` would otherwise use, ensuring the control │
│ flow in the peeled iteration is correct.\n\n5.               │
│ **Conclusion**\nThe bug is caused by an incorrect remapping  │
│ of the loop's exit condition within the `loop-peel`          │
│ transformation. The proposed fix corrects this by explicitly │
│ setting the branch condition in the terminator of the peeled │
│ latch block to the correct peeled exit condition. This       │
│ ensures that the control flow of the peeled iteration        │
│ matches the semantics of the original loop, resolving the    │
│ verification failure and producing correct code."})          │
